1. Spring Framework
Spring is an open-source Java framework for enterprise application development.
It simplifies Java development by providing reusable components.
It supports dependency injection and aspect-oriented programming.
Spring promotes loosely coupled and maintainable applications.
It is widely used with Spring Boot for modern applications.
2. Advantages of Spring
Reduces boilerplate code and simplifies development.
Supports Dependency Injection (DI) and Inversion of Control (IoC).
Easy integration with databases, web services, and security.
Makes applications modular and easy to test.
Provides high scalability and flexibility.
3. Maven Introduction
Maven is a project management and build automation tool.
It manages project dependencies automatically.
It standardizes project structure.
It compiles, tests, and packages Java applications.
It uses the pom.xml file for project configuration.
4. Maven Project Structure
src/main/java contains application source code.
src/main/resources stores configuration files.
src/test/java contains test classes.
pom.xml manages dependencies and plugins.
target/ contains compiled project files.
5. Maven Dependencies
Dependencies are external libraries used in a project.
They are declared inside pom.xml.
Maven downloads them automatically.
It manages library versions efficiently.
It avoids manual JAR file management.
6. pom.xml
pom.xml is the Project Object Model file.
It stores project information and dependencies.
It defines plugins and build configurations.
It specifies project version and packaging.
Maven reads this file during project build.
7. settings.xml
settings.xml stores Maven configuration settings.
It defines local repository location.
It can configure proxy and authentication.
It manages remote repositories.
It is stored outside the project directory.
8. Spring IoC (Inversion of Control)
IoC means Spring manages object creation.
Developers don't create objects manually.
Spring container creates and manages beans.
It reduces tight coupling.
It improves code maintainability.
9. Dependency Injection (DI)
DI is a feature of IoC.
Spring injects required objects automatically.
It supports constructor and setter injection.
DI improves code reusability.
It makes testing easier.
10. Spring Bean
A Bean is an object managed by Spring.
Beans are created inside the IoC container.
They contain business logic.
Beans can be singleton or prototype.
They are configured using XML or annotations.
11. BeanFactory
BeanFactory is the basic Spring container.
It creates beans only when required (lazy loading).
It consumes less memory.
It is suitable for small applications.
It provides basic IoC functionality.
12. ApplicationContext
ApplicationContext is an advanced Spring container.
It loads beans eagerly by default.
It supports events and internationalization.
It provides more enterprise features.
It is preferred over BeanFactory.
13. BeanFactory vs ApplicationContext
BeanFactory uses lazy initialization.
ApplicationContext uses eager initialization.
ApplicationContext supports events.
BeanFactory provides basic features.
ApplicationContext is widely used in Spring projects.
14. XML-Based Bean Configuration
Beans are defined in an XML file.
Dependencies are configured in XML.
Spring reads the XML during startup.
It separates configuration from code.
Suitable for legacy Spring applications.
15. Annotation-Based Configuration
Uses annotations instead of XML.
Common annotations include @Component, @Service, and @Repository.
Reduces XML configuration.
Improves code readability.
Preferred in modern Spring applications.
16. Aspect-Oriented Programming (AOP)
AOP separates cross-cutting concerns.
It is used for logging and security.
Improves modularity.
Uses aspects, advice, and join points.
Reduces duplicate code.
17. Spring MVC
Spring MVC is a web framework.
It follows the Model-View-Controller architecture.
It separates business logic from presentation.
Controllers handle user requests.
It is used for developing web applications.
18. Spring ORM
ORM stands for Object Relational Mapping.
It maps Java objects to database tables.
Spring integrates with Hibernate and JPA.
It reduces SQL coding.
It simplifies database operations.
19. Spring Boot
Spring Boot simplifies Spring application development.
It provides auto-configuration.
It includes an embedded Tomcat server.
It reduces configuration effort.
It is ideal for developing REST APIs and microservices.
20. Practical Benefits of Spring
Simplifies enterprise Java development.
Promotes loosely coupled architecture.
Supports rapid application development.
Improves code maintainability and testing.
Integrates easily with Maven, Hibernate, and databases.